We have hundreds of other guns currently IN STOCK, and offer some of Utah’s lowest prices! For a complete listing of my current inventory, and to purchase this and other guns online, please be sure to VISIT US ON THE WEB AT:


*** TooeleShootingSupply.com ***


Tooele Shooting Supply just received a shipment of BRAND NEW FIREARMS, including a couple of brand new, factory fresh and hard to find North American Arms Sidewinder Convertible .22lr/ .22 mag revolvers.


 I have just two in stock, and have them SALE PRICED for just $399.00 each (cash price).


North American Arms Sidewinder with Conversion – .22 Mag / .22LR Mini-Revolver – NAA-SWC

You’re likely familiar with North American Arms, the makers of the near-legendary tiny stainless steel single-action .22 caliber revolvers. Thousands ride in cops’ pockets as back-up guns, in hunters’ coats as snake guns, some are used for concealed carry and some are even handy for plinking and targeting. In the past, it’s been necessary to actually take the cylinder out of the frame of the little revolvers to load or unload them. You remove the cylinder base pin, drop the cylinder into your hand, use the base pin to knock out empties, reload then basically “reassemble” your gun. That’s fine if you only need four or five shots!

Hot off the presses at North American Arms is their newest design, the Sidewinder. By simply pulling the ejector rod forward a tiny bit, the cylinder actually swings out, just like a “real” double-action revolver. While the Sidewinder is still single action, the new model also has a genuine ejector rod and ejector star, which will push the empties out all at once, at least far enough you can pluck ’em with a fingernail. It’s definitely easier to load/unload than the other designs.

title: For Sale:  DWM 1914 NAVY LUGER 9mm -- Original, Matching
postcontent: Here's a rather scarce DWM Model 1914 Navy Luger. Chambered for the 9mm Parabellum, this Navy Luger features a 6-inch barrel and an 100-200 meter adjustable rear sight. This pistol was manufactured in 1917 and has that date properly marked on the receiver, grip frame and front sight. The Navy "Crown M" proofs appear on the left side of the receiver and underside of the barrel. The serial numbered parts are matching however the grips and firing pin are not numbered. Magazine is Navy "M" marked but has had the original number scrubbed. Overall condition is very good with some honest wear. There is some fading to the blue finish on the right side of the receiver and various high points. There is no significant rust or pitting. The grips show some wear and the left grip has the typical chip missing from beneath the safety lever. The mechanics appear to be in good working order. The bore rates about "good" with strong rifling that shows some wear and erosion in the grooves. There are NO import markings. An honest Navy Luger has become difficult to locate these days and many are faked.

postcontent: Here is My  DWM Model 1914 Navy Luger. Chambered for the 9mm Parabellum, this Navy Luger features a 6-inch barrel and an 100-200 meter adjustable rear sight. This pistol was manufactured in 1917 and has that date properly marked on the receiver, grip frame and front sight. The Navy "Crown M" proofs appear on the left side of the receiver and underside of the barrel. The serial numbered parts are matching however the grips and firing pin are not numbered. Magazine is Navy "M" marked but has had the original number scrubbed. Overall condition is very good with some honest wear. There is some fading to the blue finish on the right side of the receiver and various high points. There is no significant rust or pitting. The grips show some wear and the left grip has the typical chip missing from beneath the safety lever. The mechanics appear to be in good working order. The bore rates about "good" with strong rifling that shows some wear and erosion in the grooves. There are NO import markings. An honest Navy Luger has become difficult to locate these days and many are faked...this is a good one

title: For Sale/Trade:  45acp VZ24 Mauser
postcontent:
Here's one you won't see for sale very often: 

I am selling my project rifle for the past few months, a VZ24 converted to 45acp (using 1911 magazines) via a Rhineland Arms conversion kit.  I've put a lot of time, effort, and money into this conversion. This rifle started life as a VZ24 with a scrubbed receiver and mismatching parts.  I then bought a Rhineland Arms 45acp conversion kit with a military contour barrel intending to rebuild it as a "Mini-Mauser" of sorts.  Most of the work was done professionally by Jeff at Rangemasters in Lebanon, but I have sunk a large amount of time into it as well. The rifle is accurate and has practically no kick, but there are some small issues:

-If you fully load your magazine, the very first round has a tendency to nosedive into the feed ramp, getting stuck.  If you download your magazine by 1, you will not have any problems.  The rifle used to only feed with 4 rounds in the magazine until Jeff basically built a new feed ramp into the rifle.  Now it'll feed if you have 7 rounds loaded out of an 8 round magazine, which I count as a win. 

-To insert a new magazine, you have to press the magazine release.  A different magazine button (1911, extended variety) might fix that issue, but it's not really a big enough deal that I felt the need to replace it. 

You also have to work the bolt quickly and smoothly for it to feed correctly, but that is something that the Rhineland Arms manual points as well.  The bayonet lug is acraglassed into the stock, and is for decoration only - don't actually try to mount a bayonet on it.  

Most of the original metal parts have a worn blue finish on it.  The new barrel was cold blued to try to match that pattern.  It ended up being a bit darker than the other metal parts in areas, but should wear to be blend in a bit better.


It's a nice little rifle that shoots well.  I just am not as interested in it as I used to be, so I am letting it go.  Asking for $700, which is less than what I have put into it for materials and gunsmithing fees.  No lowballers, I am patient enough to wait for a fair deal.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Should businesses use this site as their personal store front?
postcontent:
Wow!  I'm all for the small business owner trying to get some advertisement and make some money...but really?  I used to love coming to this site and look what all the 'private sellers' have to offer, but now it's becoming really annoying knowing that I have to go through 15+ pages just find something from a private seller.  

If it was a few items, fine.  But 15+ PAGES?  I didn't even see how many more pages there were, I just got frustrated and decided to write this note after I started clicking page after page.  Maybe these businesses should take out an ad rather than to use it as their own personal online store.  

Again, nothing against these businesses, but it sure doesn't help us private sellers just trying to get rid of an item or two because people don't/won't go through 20 pages just to see a private sale.  Does this bother anyone else?  I know these people have a 'vendor' account and are allowed to post a lot, but can't they use some moderation?
